 ‘to press’."]},{"name":"Prestwich","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from a place in Lancashire (now Greater Manchester), so called from Old English <i>prēost</i> ‘priest’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘outlying settlement’, or from other places with the same derivation. Variants such as <i>Prestidge</i>, <i>Prestage</i>, etc., parallel the local pronunciation of the Lancashire name. Compare   Preston  ."]}]},{"name":"Eleanor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":58,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Eleanor Preston was born about 1397, in Buckinghamshire, England as the daughter of Hugh Preston. She had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with Henry Brudenell."},"et":{"Abt 1397–":"umbes 1397–Surnud","1397–Female":"1397–Surnud","1393–Male":"1393–Surnud","1420–1469":"1420–1469","1421–Male":"1421–Surnud","1423–Male":"1423–Surnud","1442–1522":"1442–1522","1372–Male":"1372–Surnud","1372":"1372","1393":"1393","abt 1421":"umbes 1421","abt 1423":"umbes 1423","1469":"1469","1522":"1522","1423":"1423","1455":"1455","1421":"1421","Abt 1397":"umbes 1397","1420":"1420","1442":"1442","1397":"1397","Amersham, Buckinghamshire, England":"Amersham, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","of Raans, Bucks., Eng.":"Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1397–":"noin 1397–Kuollut","1397–Female":"1397–Kuollut","1393–Male":"1393–Kuollut","1420–1469":"1420–1469","1421–Male":"1421–Kuollut","1423–Male":"1423–Kuollut","1442–1522":"1442–1522","1372–Male":"1372–Kuollut","1372":"1372","1393":"1393","abt 1421":"noin 1421","abt 1423":"noin 1423","1469":"1469","1522":"1522","1423":"1423","1455":"1455","1421":"1421","Abt 1397":"noin 1397","1420":"1420","1442":"1442","1397":"1397","Amersham, Buckinghamshire, England":"Amersham, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","of Raans, Bucks., Eng.":"Buckinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1397–":"environ 1397–Décédée","1397–Female":"1397–Décédée","1393–Male":"1393–Décédé","1420–1469":"1420–1469","1421–Male":"1421–Décédé","1423–Male":"1423–Décédé","1442–1522":